=== 20th century ===
The first U.S. law that restricted the distribution and use of certain drugs was the [[Harrison_Narcotics_Tax_Act|Harrison Narcotics Tax Act]] of 1914. The first local laws came as early as 1860.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/heroin/etc/history.html |title=Opium Throughout History |publisher=PBS Frontline |accessdate=2010-10-08}}</ref> In 1919, the United States passed the [[美國憲法第十八修正案|18th Amendment]], prohibiting the sale, manufacture, and transportation of [[乙醇|alcohol]], with exceptions for religious and medical use. In 1920, the United States passed the [[National_Prohibition_Act|National Prohibition Act]] (Volstead Act), enacted to carry out the provisions in law of the 18th Amendment.

The [[Federal_Bureau_of_Narcotics|Federal Bureau of Narcotics]] was established in the [[美国财政部|United States Department of the Treasury]] by an act of June 14, 1930 (46 Stat. 585).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archives.gov/research/guide-fed-records/groups/170.html#170.3 |title=Records of the Drug Enforcement Administration DEA |publisher=Archives.gov |accessdate=2011-03-27}}</ref> In 1933, [[禁酒時期|the federal prohibition for alcohol]] was repealed by passage of the [[美利坚合众国宪法第二十一条修正案|21st Amendment]]. In 1935, President [[富兰克林·德拉诺·罗斯福|Franklin D. Roosevelt]] publicly supported the adoption of the [[Uniform_State_Narcotic_Drug_Act|Uniform State Narcotic Drug Act]]. ''[[纽约时报|The New York Times]]'' used the headline "Roosevelt Asks Narcotic War Aid".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.druglibrary.net/schaffer/History/e1930/rooseveltasks.htm |title=ROOSEVELT ASKS NARCOTIC WAR AID, 1935 |publisher=Druglibrary.net |accessdate=2011-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=15024 |title=Letter to the World Narcotic Defense Association. March 21, 1935 |publisher=Presidency.ucsb.edu |accessdate=2011-03-27}}</ref>

In 1937, the [[Marihuana_Tax_Act_of_1937|Marihuana Tax Act of 1937]] was passed. Several scholars have claimed that the goal was to destroy the hemp industry,<ref name="nafta-neocolonialism-129">{{Cite book|last1=French|first1=Laurence|first2=Magdaleno|last2=Manzanárez|title=NAFTA & neocolonialism: comparative criminal, human & social justice|publisher=University Press of America|year=2004|page=129|isbn=978-0-7618-2890-7|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4ozF1Yg-c4MC&pg=PA129}}</ref><ref>Earlywine, 2005: [https://books.google.com/books?id=r9wPbxMAG8cC&pg=PA24 p. 24]</ref><ref name="under-influence-55">Peet, 2004: [https://books.google.com/?id=uC0_YznYjScC&pg=PA55 p. 55]</ref> largely as an effort of businessmen [[安德鲁·W·梅隆|Andrew Mellon]], [[威廉·赫斯特|Randolph Hearst]], and the [[杜邦家族|Du Pont family]].<ref name="nafta-neocolonialism-129" /><ref name="under-influence-55" /> These scholars argue that with the invention of the [[decorticator|decorticator]], hemp became a very cheap substitute for the [[木浆|paper pulp]] that was used in the newspaper industry.<ref name="nafta-neocolonialism-129" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Bound in twine: the history and ecology of the henequen-wheat complex for Mexico and the American and Canadian Plains, 1880–1950|author=Sterling Evans|publisher=Texas A&M University Press|year=2007|isbn=978-1-58544-596-7|page=27|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_wFkZgyuGFAC&pg=PA27}}</ref> These scholars believe that Hearst felt{{dubious|date=March 2015}} that this was a threat to his extensive timber holdings.  Mellon, [[美国财政部长|United States Secretary of the Treasury]] and the wealthiest man in America, had invested heavily in the [[杜邦|DuPont]]'s new synthetic fiber, nylon, and considered {{dubious|date=March 2015}} its success to depend on its replacement of the traditional resource, hemp.<ref name="nafta-neocolonialism-129" /><ref>{{cite book|editor=Evans, Sterling|title=The borderlands of the American and Canadian Wests: essays on regional history of the forty-ninth parallel|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|year=2006|isbn=978-0-8032-1826-0|page=199|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xBELvIaDXxAC&pg=PA199}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Gerber, Rudolph Joseph|title=Legalizing marijuana: drug policy reform and prohibition politics|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=2004|isbn=978-0-275-97448-0|page=7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WMOdI9pC-gEC&pg=PA7}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Earleywine, Mitchell|title=Understanding marijuana: a new look at the scientific evidence|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2005|isbn=978-0-19-518295-8|page=231|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r9wPbxMAG8cC&pg=PA231}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Robinson, Matthew B.  |author2=Scherlen, Renee G. |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Lies, damned lies, and drug war statistics: a critical analysis of claims made by the office of National Drug Control Policy|publisher=SUNY Press|year=2007|isbn=978-0-7914-6975-0|page=12|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dwGpsNjv_1kC&pg=PA12}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Rowe, Thomas C.|title=Federal narcotics laws and the war on drugs: money down a rat hole|publisher=Psychology Press|year=2006|isbn=978-0-7890-2808-2|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v1tz6nP6fdwC&pg=PA26}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editors=Sullivan, Larry E. et al.|title=Encyclopedia of Law Enforcement: Federal|publisher=SAGE|year=2005|isbn=978-0-7619-2649-8|page=747|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FtgYAAAAIAAJ&q=hearst+hemp&dq=hearst+hemp}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Lusane, Clarence|authorlink=Clarence Lusane|title=Pipe dream blues: racism and the war on drugs|publisher=South End Press|year=1991|isbn=978-0-89608-410-0|pages=37–38|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=flIjcQBwu68C&pg=PA37}}</ref> However, there were circumstances that contradict these claims. One reason for doubts about those claims is that the new decorticators did not perform fully satisfactorily in commercial production.<ref name="Dew">{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/fiberproductioni518dewe#page/66/mode/2up|author=Dewey LH|title=Fiber production in the western hemisphere|date=1943|page=67|publisher=United States Printing Office, Washington|accessdate=2015-02-25}}</ref> To produce fiber from hemp was a labor-intensive process if you include harvest, transport and processing. Technological developments decreased the labor with hemp but not sufficient to eliminate this disadvantage.<ref>[http://www.aae.wisc.edu/pubs/sps/pdf/stpap443.pdf T. Randall Fortenbery and Michael Bennett: Is Industrial Hemp Worth Further Study in the US? A Survey of the Literature,  Department of Agricultural and Applied Economics, University of Wisconsin – Ma7dison. July 2001]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://druglibrary.org/schaffer/library/hemp_conspiracy.htm|title=Was there a conspiracy to outlaw hemp because it was a threat to theDuPonts and other industrial interests?|publisher=}}</ref>

On October 27, 1970, Congress passes the [[Comprehensive_Drug_Abuse_Prevention_and_Control_Act_of_1970|Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act of 1970]], which, among other things, categorizes controlled substances based on their medicinal use and potential for addiction.<ref name="frontline" /> In 1971, two congressmen released an explosive report on the growing heroin epidemic among U.S. servicemen in Vietnam; ten to fifteen percent of the servicemen were addicted to heroin, and President Nixon declared drug abuse to be "public enemy number one".<ref name="frontline" /><ref name="dupoint">[http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/drugs/interviews/dupont.html WGBH educational foundation. Interview with Dr. Robert Dupoint]. Pbs.org (February 18, 1970).</ref>

Although Nixon declared "drug abuse" to be public enemy number one in 1971,<ref name=Chronology>{{cite web|title=Thirty Years of America's Drug War|url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/drugs/cron/|work=Frontline|publisher=PBS|accessdate=2012-10-19}}</ref> the policies that his administration implemented as part of the [[Comprehensive_Drug_Abuse_Prevention_and_Control_Act_of_1970|Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act of 1970]] were a continuation of drug prohibition policies in the U.S., which started in 1914.<ref name=frontline>[http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/drugs/cron/ Thirty Years of America's Drug War, a Chronology]. [[Frontline_(U.S._TV_series)|Frontline (U.S. TV series)]].</ref><ref name=npr>[http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=9252490 Timeline: America's War on Drugs]. April 2, 2007. [[全国公共广播电台|NPR]].</ref>

<blockquote>"The Nixon campaign in 1968, and the Nixon White House after that, had two enemies: the antiwar left and black people. You understand what I'm saying? We knew we couldn't make it illegal to be either against the war or black, but by getting the public to associate the hippies with marijuana and blacks with heroin, and then criminalizing both heavily, we could disrupt those communities. We could arrest their leaders, raid their homes, break up their meetings, and vilify them night after night on the evening news. Did we know we were lying about the drugs? Of course we did."<br/> - [[John_Ehrlichman|John Ehrlichman]], to Dan Baum<ref>http://harpers.org/author/danbaum/</ref><ref>http://www.danbaum.com/</ref><ref>http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/05/08/dan-baum-fired-by-inew-yo_n_200457.html</ref> for [[哈泼斯杂志|Harper's Magazine]]<ref>http://harpers.org/archive/2016/04/legalize-it-all/?single=1</ref> in 1994, about President [[理查德·尼克松|Richard Nixon]]'s war on drugs, declared in 1971.<ref>http://www.vox.com/2016/3/22/11278760/war-on-drugs-racism-nixon</ref><ref>[[John_Ehrlichman#War_on_drugs|John Ehrlichman § War on drugs]]</ref></blockquote>

In 1973, the [[美国缉毒局|Drug Enforcement Administration]] was created to replace the [[麻醉药物和危险药物管理局|Bureau of Narcotics and Dangerous Drugs]].<ref name="frontline" />

The Nixon Administration also repealed the federal 2–10-year [[mandatory_sentencing|mandatory minimum sentences]] for  possession of marijuana and started federal demand reduction programs and drug-treatment programs. [[Robert_DuPont|Robert DuPont]], the "Drug czar" in the Nixon Administration, stated it would be more accurate to say that Nixon ended, rather than launched, the "war on drugs".  DuPont also argued that it was the proponents of drug legalization that popularized the term "war on drugs".<ref name="dup2"/>{{Unreliable source?|date=February 2014}}

In 1982, Vice President [[乔治·H·W·布什|George H. W. Bush]] and his aides began pushing for the involvement of the CIA and U.S. military in drug interdiction efforts.<ref>Scott and Marshall, 1991: p. 2</ref>[[File:Fuerza_del_Estado_Michoacán.jpg|thumb]] claims nearly 50,000 lives each year.]]
The [[Office_of_National_Drug_Control_Policy|Office of National Drug Control Policy]] (ONDCP) was originally established by the National Narcotics Leadership Act of 1988,<ref>[[National_Narcotics_Leadership_Act_of_1988|National Narcotics Leadership Act of 1988]] (Anti–Drug Abuse Act of 1988), {{USStatute|100|690|102|4181|1988|11|18}}</ref><ref>{{citation | title= B-303495, Office of National Drug Control Policy – Video News Release | publisher= [[Government_Accountability_Office|Government Accountability Office]] | date= 2005-01-04 | last= Gamboa | first= Anthony H. | at= footnote 6, page 3 | url= http://www.gao.gov/decisions/appro/303495.pdf}}</ref> which mandated a national anti-drug media campaign for youth, which would later become the [[National_Youth_Anti-Drug_Media_Campaign|National Youth Anti-Drug Media Campaign]].<ref>Treasury and General Government Appropriations Act of 1998, {{USPL|105|61}}, {{USStat|111|1272}}, at 111 Stat. 1294</ref> The director of ONDCP is commonly known as the [[Drug_czar|Drug czar]],<ref name="frontline" /> and it was first implemented in 1989 under President [[乔治·H·W·布什|George H. W. Bush]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/drugs/cron/ |title=frontline: drug wars: thirty years of America's drug war |publisher=PBS |accessdate=2011-03-27}}</ref> and raised to cabinet-level status by [[比尔·克林顿|Bill Clinton]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/tom-angell/bill-clinton-drug-war_b_2271885.html | title=Does Bill Clinton Support Legalizing Marijuana? | work=Huffington Post | date=2012-12-10 | accessdate=2014-10-28 | author=Angell, Tom}}</ref> These activities were subsequently funded by the Treasury and General Government Appropriations Act of 1998.<ref>[[Treasury_and_General_Government_Appropriations_Act_of_1998|Treasury and General Government Appropriations Act of 1998]], {{USPL|105|61}}, {{USStat|111|1272}}</ref><ref>{{citation | title= GAO-06-818, ONDCP Media Campaign: Contractor's National Evaluation Did Not Find That the Youth Anti-Drug Media Campaign Was Effective in Reducing Youth Drug Use | publisher= [[Government_Accountability_Office|Government Accountability Office]] | date= August 2006 | page= 1 | url= http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d06818.pdf }}</ref> The Drug-Free Media Campaign Act of 1998 codified the  campaign at {{USC|21|1708}}.<ref>Drug-Free Media Campaign Act of 1998 (Omnibus Consolidated and Emergency Supplemental Appropriations Act, 1999), {{USStatute|105|277|112|268|1998|10|21}}, at 112 Stat. 2681-752</ref>

=== 21st century ===
The [[Global_Commission_on_Drug_Policy|Global Commission on Drug Policy]] released a report on June 2, 2011 alleging that "The War On Drugs Has Failed".  The commissioned was made up of 22 self-appointed members including a number of prominent international politicians and writers. U.S. Surgeon General [[Regina_Benjamin|Regina Benjamin]] also released the first ever National Prevention Strategy.<ref>[http://www.healthcare.gov/center/councils/nphpphc/strategy/index.html National Prevention Strategy, June 16, 2011]. Healthcare.gov (June 16, 2011). {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902021349/http://www.healthcare.gov/center/councils/nphpphc/strategy/index.html |date=2011-09-02 }}</ref>

On May 21, 2012, the U.S. Government published an updated version of its Drug Policy.<ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/ondcp/policy-and-research/principles-of-modern-drug-policy Principles of Modern Drug Policy]. Whitehouse.gov.</ref> The director of [[ONDCP|ONDCP]] stated simultaneously that this policy is something different from the "War on Drugs":
* The U.S Government sees the policy as a "third way" approach to drug control; an approach that is based on the results of a huge investment in research from some of the world's preeminent scholars on disease of substance abuse.
* The policy does not see drug legalization as the "silver bullet" solution to drug control.
* It is not a policy where success is measured by the number of arrests made or prisons built.<ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/ondcp/news-releases-remarks/principles-of-modern-drug-policy-directors-remarks-at-the-world-federation-against-drugs Statement of the Government of the United States of America World Federation Against Drugs 3rd World Forum, May 21, 2012, Stockholm, Sweden]. Whitehouse.gov (September 21, 2012).</ref>

At the same meeting was a declaration signed by the representatives of Italy, the Russian Federation, Sweden, the United Kingdom and the United States in line with this:
"Our approach must be a balanced one, combining effective enforcement to restrict the supply of drugs, with efforts to reduce demand and build recovery; supporting people to live a life free of addiction".<ref>[http://www.wfad.se/images/articles/Final_statement_WFAD.pdf Joint statement For a humane and balanced drug policy, Stockholm 20 May 2012]. (PDF).</ref>

In March 2016 the [[国际麻醉药管制委员会|International Narcotics Control Board]] stated that the International Drug Control treaties do not mandata a "war on drugs".<ref>[http://www.unis.unvienna.org/unis/en/pressrels/2016/unisnar1264.html INCB Report 2015 - Press material] United Nations Information Service 2.3.2016.</ref>
